# Change to a time series
fortifiedTS <- ts(wines$Fortified, start = c(1980, 1), frequency = 12)

plot(fortifiedTS)

# Now decompose the ts
fortifiedDecomp <- decompose(fortifiedTS)

# See the random
plot(wineR <- fortifiedDecomp$random) #theres no pattern in the noise, so we should look at an additive model.

# Partition
winesTRAIN <- wines[1:168,]
trainTS <- ts(winesTRAIN$Fortified, start = c(1980, 1), frequency = 12)

winesVALIDATION <- wines[169:180,]
validationTS  <- ts(winesVALIDATION$Fortified, start = c(1980, 1), frequency = 12)

# Re-Fit HW with training partition
monthHW <- HoltWinters(trainTS, beta = FALSE, gamma = .4, seasonal = 'additive')
plot(monthHW)

# Make predictions on validation
validForecasts <- predict(monthHW, 2)

validForecasts 
##           Jan      Feb
## 1994 1129.294 1348.382
#January 1994 = 1129.294
#February 1994 = 1348.382

# Organize & Compare
(validationDF <- data.frame(idx = seq_along(validForecasts),
                            original = winesVALIDATION$Fortified,
                            fit = validForecasts)[1:2,])
##   idx original      fit
## 1   1     1154 1129.294
## 2   2     1568 1348.382
# Examine visual fit
ggplot(validationDF) +
  geom_line(aes(x=idx, y=original)) +
  geom_line(aes(x=idx, y=fit), colour='red') + theme_bw()

# Get RMSE
RMSE(validationDF$original, validationDF$fit)
## [1] 156.2726
MAPE(validationDF$original, validationDF$fit)
## [1] 0.09237625
#season length (gamma) = 0.4 generates the smallest RMSE.

#Stocks Question

stockChk <- function(tickerSymbol='AAPL', lookBack =365, kpi = 'macd', recommendation = 'NOT ENTERED'){
  
  # Libs
  require(TTR)
  require(quantmod)
  require(dygraphs)
  require(htmltools)
  require(htmlwidgets)
  
  # Data & Subset
  print(paste('looking up your tickerSymbol:',tickerSymbol))
  x <- getSymbols(tickerSymbol, auto.assign=FALSE)
  x<- tail(x, lookBack)
  
  # Find the closing price column
  closeIdx <- grep('Close', names(x))
  
  # Calc indicators
  if(kpi == 'macd'){
    xKPI <- MACD(x[,closeIdx],
                 nFast = 12, nSlow = 26, nSig = 9, 
                 maType="SMA", percent = T)
  }
  if(kpi == 'rsi'){
    xKPI <-RSI(x[,closeIdx], maType="SMA", n =14)
  }
  if(kpi =='sma'){
    xKPI <-SMA(x[,closeIdx], 50)
    yKPI <-SMA(x[,closeIdx], 200)
  }
  
  # Visual Titles
  closingTitle <- paste('Daily Closing Price of ', tickerSymbol)
  candleTitle <- paste('Candlestick of ', tickerSymbol)
  kpiTitle <- paste(kpi, 'for', tickerSymbol, 'says to ',recommendation)
  
  # Construct kpi visuals
  if(kpi=='sma'){
    smaData <- cbind(x[,closeIdx],xKPI, yKPI) 
    kpiPlot <- dygraph(smaData, 
                       group = "Price", height = 200, 
                       width = "100%", main = kpiTitle) %>%
      dyRangeSelector()
  }
  if(kpi=='rsi'){
    kpiPlot <- dygraph(xKPI, 
                       group = "Price", height = 200, 
                       width = "100%", main = kpiTitle) %>%
      dyLimit(30, label = 'OverSold') %>%
      dyLimit(70, label = 'OverBought') %>%
      dyRangeSelector()
  }
  if(kpi=='macd'){
    kpiPlot <- dygraph(xKPI,
                       group = "Price", height = 200, 
                       width = "100%", main = kpiTitle) %>%
      dySeries('macd',label='MACD') %>%
      dySeries('signal',label='SIGNAL') %>%
      dyRangeSelector()
  }
  
  dashboard <- browsable(
    tagList(
      dygraph(x[,closeIdx], 
              group = "Price",height = 200, 
              width = "100%", main = closingTitle),
      dygraph(x[,1:4],
              group = "Price",height = 200, 
              width = "100%", main = candleTitle) %>%
        dyCandlestick(),kpiPlot))
  
  return(dashboard)
}

stockChk('MTB', kpi='macd', lookBack = 365, recommendation='buy')

#1. I'll use the MACD (Moving Average Convergence Divergence) indicator. It measures the difference between the 12-day and 26-day moving averages, then takes the 9-day moving average as a comparison signal, hoping to indicate when an investor can capture the momentum in changing stock prices. If the MACD indicator is converging above the signal, that means money is moving into the stock and the recommendation is to buy.
#2. I chose M&T Bank Corporation and the Kraft Heinz Company. Since the indicator is converging above the signal for the latest available data, the recommendation is to buy both stocks.
